{#- VARIANT DETAIL (definition) — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qbo-int-expensify-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">What an Expensify&ndash;QuickBooks integration does.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Expensify is a third-party expense and receipt-management tool &mdash; it isn&rsquo;t part of QuickBooks. Employees use it to capture receipts (usually by photographing them on their phone), code each expense to a category, and assemble those expenses into a report that goes through an approval flow. The integration is the connection that takes an <em>approved</em> Expensify report and pushes it into QuickBooks Online so you don&rsquo;t re-key any of it.</p>
      <p>How that report lands in QuickBooks depends on how you configure the sync. An approved report can post as <em>bills</em> (a payable you&rsquo;ll pay later), as <em>expenses</em> (spend already paid), or as <em>journal entries</em>, and the right choice depends on whether the spend was reimbursable or paid on a company card. This is where the setup earns its keep: each Expensify category has to be mapped to the correct account in your chart of accounts, and the reimbursable-vs-card distinction has to be handled deliberately. Mapping that&rsquo;s left at defaults dumps expenses into <em>Uncategorized</em>; card expenses synced from Expensify that are also arriving through the <a href="/quickbooks/online/features/bank-feeds/">bank feed</a> get counted twice.</p>
      <p>The integration removes the manual data entry of typing expenses into QuickBooks, but it doesn&rsquo;t decide the accounting for you. We describe the integration as it actually works &mdash; we don&rsquo;t claim capabilities it doesn&rsquo;t have, and we&rsquo;re independent of both Expensify and Intuit.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

